<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 92 / Foreign Exchanges and Money Markets: Testing times for
Dollars
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The dollar is likely to come under further pressure this week after last
week's downward shift. Wide interest rate differentials with Europe, and
continued confusing signals about US economic recovery may hinder its
progress.
Consumer confidence shot up in May, but M2 growth fell short of the Federal
Reserve's target range. Attention this week will focus on non-farm payroll
data for May and the National Association of Purchasing Managers' index.
Economists are forecasting that around 103,000 new jobs were created in May,
less than in April but greater than the average number of jobs created per
month since the second quarter of last year.
After the Bank of Japan's aggressive buying of the Yen last week, traders
said they would be watching closely to see how firm the Japanese currency
goes over the next few weeks. Mr Jim O'Neill, head of research at Swiss Bank
Corporation expects to see the Yen hit 124 against the dollar.
'The Bank of Japan appears to be sending a message loud and clear that it
would like to see a stronger yen,' he said.
According to Mr Gerard Lyons at DKB International, the Japanese Bank,
trading partners have been pressurising Japan to reduce the size of its
trade surplus. At the last G7 meeting in Washington the weakness of the yen
was singled out as a hindrance. The Japanese government's apparent desire to
strengthen the yen has probably been spurred by the prospect of the World
Economic Summit in Munich next month.
Tomorrow the Danes go to the polls in a referendum on whether Denmark should
ratify the Maastricht treaty on Emu. Traders said the result was enough in
doubt to keep the EMS currencies on edge.
</TEXT>
