FT  01 JUN 92 / Dowty moves to shore up bid defence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DOWTY Group, the aerospace and information technology group, could this week
bolster its defence against the hostile Pounds 494m bid from TI, the
specialist engineering company, with the help of payments on a cancelled
Ministry of Defence contract.
Dowty could take a Pounds 3m-Pounds 4m cancellation payment as an
exceptional item in the year to March, increasing the estimated profit by at
least 10 per cent to more than Pounds 32m. It surprised analysts 12 days ago
by estimating 1992 profits of at least Pounds 29m, some 25 per cent above
most City forecasts before the bid.
The MoD payment, if it were in the 1992 accounts, would further lift the
Cheltenham-based group's apparent recovery from the downturn in the
aerospace market and its involvement in the information technology industry.
Dowty is also likely to bring forward, from June 16, its audited preliminary
results to dispel scepticism among analysts and shareholders about the
quality of its Pounds 29m profits estimate. Publishing these results before
TI's bid closes on June 10 would allow shareholders to estimate 1993
profits, a decisive figure on which Dowty's independence turns.
A TI spokesman yesterday welcomed the opportunity to 'see Dowty's full
accounts and the answers to the many questions surrounding them'.
In a letter to Dowty's shareholders over the weekend, TI attacked the
profits estimate. It questioned restructuring and closure provisions and the
extent to which Dowty has capitalised the development costs of the
loss-making Cognito two-way paging company.
The MoD payment which Dowty is now likely to bring into its 1992 profits
relates to a naval contract cancelled last year but on which payment terms
have only 'recently' been agreed, according to a Dowty adviser. The costs of
the contract were incurred during the last financial year but very little of
the benefit was included in Dowty's profit estimate of 'not less than Pounds
29m', the adviser said.
As the bid enters its closing stages, advisers from both sides are stepping
up their presentations to institutional investors. Dowty says while it made
mistakes in the past, including the disastrous move into information
technology, it has now stripped out a lot of costs and refocused.
