<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 92 / Construction Contracts: French tourist attraction
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A major clean up programme is to be undertaken at the bay surrounding
Mont-Saint Michel because it has been severely polluted by untreated waste.
Roughly 1.5m visitors a year come to Mont-Saint Michel, a rocky isle topped
by a Benedictine abbey and connected to the mainland by a causeway. Despite
the multitude of visitors, hotels and restaurants on the isle have dumped
untreated waste water into the bay.
Mr Pierre-Frederic Teniere-Buchot, a regional water official, said the
cleanup plan would cost FFr20m (Pounds 2.03m) and would establish a waste
treatment system within two years. He also forecast that the cost of water
was likely to increase by 180 per cent.
The project will entail the temporary removal of the cobblestones paving the
isle's narrow main street. The bay, already a subject of environmental
concern, has been shrinking in size because of the encroachment of silt.
</TEXT>
