<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 92 / Mirror staff may leave NUJ
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NATIONAL Union of Journalists (NUJ) was threatened with a split
yesterday after one of its largest office branches voted to leave the union.
Members of the 288-strong Daily Mirror chapel decided by 94 votes to 76 not
to stay in the NUJ. They will decide their next move on Wednesday.
One possibility is that they will join the British Association of
Journalists, which is being set up by Mr Steve Turner, a former Daily Mirror
journalist, who was dismissed as general secretary last year after clashes
with the union's executive.
Many Mirror journalists are angry about the way Mr Turner was treated, and
some believe a breakaway organisation would attract journalists at other
newspapers because of dissatisfaction with what are perceived as the NUJ's
leftwing policies.
Union breakaways usually struggle to win large memberships in the face of
difficulties in gaining affiliation to the Trades Union Congress and
resistance to change from members of the organisation.
Leaders of the Nupe public-service union yesterday won the backing of their
annual conference for plans to merge with the Nalgo and Cohse public-service
unions. The merger would create a 1.5m-strong union.
Assuming the annual conferences of Nalgo and Cohse also agree to the merger
plans later this month, members will be asked to vote on the issue later in
the year. The merger would go ahead in July next year.
</TEXT>
