<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 92 / Sexual harassment reported
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH women face sexual harassment in most workplaces and all sectors of
employment, according to IRS, a independent employment research group.
More than half the 132 employers in the survey published today in IRS
Employment Trends journal said complaints of sexual harassment had been made
at their workplaces, with 46 per cent saying cases had been reported during
the past year.
Almost nine out of 10 harassment complaints are upheld after internal
investigations. Proven harassers can face dismissal, according to almost
half of employers, while 57 per cent said they issued formal warnings or
took disciplinary action.
Only one employer said sexual harassment was not a disciplinary offence,
although one in 10 said that the position was 'not clear'.
Almost four employers in five said sexual harassment was a 'fairly important
problem' compared with 15 per cent who said it was a 'major problem'. Three
per cent said they did not see it as a problem.
The survey shows that awareness of the issue is growing in the private
sector, where one in five employers have policy statements. Half of
public-sector employers said they had policy statements on sexual
harassment.
Sexual Harassment at the Workplace, by Janet Egan. IRS Employment Trends
513. IRS, 18-20 Highbury Place, London N5 1QP. Pounds 350 by annual
subscription.
</TEXT>
