<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 92 / CBI urges law on squatting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CONFEDERATION of British Industry has called for squatting in commercial
buildings to be made a criminal offence.
It says squatting in shops, factories and offices is costing UK companies
thousands of pounds a year.
In Scotland, offenders can be fined or jailed for squatting in commercial or
residential property. In England and Wales, the only remedy is an expensive
and time-consuming civil action.
The CBI said that, apart from legal action, companies had to pay to repair
property damage, replace stolen or damaged stock and remove rubbish. Also
their insurance premiums went up.
