<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 92 / Inquiry called for on Tory funding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LEADER of the Labour opposition on Westminster City Council said
yesterday that he was seeking an Inland Revenue investigation into a
registered charity, the Foundation for Business Responsibilities, to
discover if it has breached laws concerning tax relief for charities.
The FBR has been criticised by the Charity Commission in a letter to
Westminster Labour leader Mr Andrew Dismore for making unauthorised payments
to a public-relations company, Marketforce Communications. The company was
employed by Westminster council's Conservatives to promote the party before
the May 1990 local elections.
The commission's rules bar charities from engaging in political activities.
The FBR was established in 1972 as an educational trust.
The 1990 elections saw the Tories increase their majority over Labour - the
Conservatives now hold 45 seats and Labour 15, out of the total 60 on
Westminster council.
Mr Dismore complained to the Charity Commission about FBR funding the Tory
election campaign, and the commission has now backed that complaint.
Its letter to Mr Dismore said the charity paid more than Pounds 98,000 to
Marketforce. The commission found that the payment infringed charity rules.
The money has been repaid to the charity by its trustees, although yesterday
it was still not clear where the refund came from.
Dame Shirley Porter, the Conservative leader of the council at the time, who
has just ended her term of office as Lord Mayor of London, has been sent a
letter from Mr Dismore, asking for clarification of her involvement with the
use of the charity's funds for politically motivated public relations work
for her party.
A representative of Dame Shirley yesterday denied that she had any
connection with the FBR.
Mr Michael Ivens, director of the FBR, who also runs the free-market
pressure group Aims of Industry, yesterday also declined to comment on the
matter.
Mr Dismore said that, after the commission's criticism of the FBR, the exact
relationship between it, Marketforce and the Conservative party at
Westminster council should be clarified. He added that Dame Shirley 'should
come clean and tell us what she was up to'.
</TEXT>
