<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAY 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow slips back after hitting
record high
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US EQUITIES ended the day modestly lower yesterday after soaring to record
levels in the morning yesterday, bolstered by a strong first quarter GDP
advance, lower bond market yields and buoyant overseas markets, writes Karen
Zagor in New York.
The day started on a strong note, following Thursday's record close, and the
Dow Jones Industrial Average passed the important 3,400 level within minutes
of opening and remained above that level until the last half hour of
trading. Contributing to the bullishness was a report that GDP had risen 2.4
per cent in the first quarter, its most substantial gain since the same
period of 1989.
The Dow's failure to hold above 3,400, however, caused some analysts to
speculate that the market is now set to turn lower.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed at 3,396.88, down 1.55 in moderately
heavy volume of more than 204m shares. Advancing issues led those declining
by 966 to 726. While the more broadly-based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 also moved
lower, sliding 1.39 to 415.35, the Nasdaq composite bucked the trend to rise
4.82 to 585.31. On Thursday, the Dow rose 27.99 to 3,398.43.
A second day of declining bond yields also bolstered the equity market
through most of the day. In late trading, the treasury's benchmark 30-year
bond was  1/4 higher at 101 27/32 , yielding 7.833 per cent.
Airline stocks recovered some of their previous day's losses. Shares in AMR,
parent of American Airlines, firmed Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 63 1/4 , Delta
Airlines was unchanged at Dollars 57; UAL, parent of United Airlines, added
Dollars 4 3/8 to Dollars 118 3/8 and USAir was Dollars 1/2 higher at Dollars
12 5/8 .
Pharmaceutical company stocks saw active trading, with Merck slipping
Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 50 1/4 and Glaxo's ADR's up Dollars  1/2 to Dollars
28 1/4 .
Trading was heavy in a number of blue-chip stocks including General Motors,
up Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 39 7/8 and Citicorp, Dollars  1/8 higher at
Dollars 18 5/8 .
Shares in Centel, the Chicago-based local phone company which has agreed to
merge with Sprint at a price well under market valuations, edged Dollars
1/8 higher to Dollars 32 after plunging Dollars 10 1/2 a day earlier.
Sprint, which dropped Dollars 1 3/8 on Thursday, lost Dollars  1/8 to
Dollars 23.
Among other cellular phone stocks which were battered on the Centel merger
news, GTE regained Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 31 3/8 , McCaw Cellular eased
Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 27 1/4 , and Lin Broadcasting slipped Dollars 1 to
Dollars 67.
Shares in Rockefeller Center, the real estate investment trust, tumbled
Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 14 3/8 after Lehman Brothers downgraded its rating
on the stock amid concerns that Rockefeller might cut its dividend.
Canada
TORONTO posted a small advance in moderate trading. Based on preliminary
figures, the composite index was up 12.59 points, or 0.37 per cent, to
3,387.93, for a gain on the week of about 16 points. Advances led declines
by 317 to 264, volume fell to 20.404m shares from 25.594m shares on
Thursday, and trading value was CDollars 223.8m against CDollars 324.7m.
Royal Bank of Canada, up  3/4 to 23 1/4 , reported slightly lower
second-quarter earnings. It said it has classified CDollars 510m of its
CDollars 780m of loans to Olympia &amp; York as non-performing.
</TEXT>
