FT  30 MAY 92 / Grade appeals to OFT over football contract
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL GRADE, chief executive of Channel 4, yesterday appealed to the
Office of Fair Trading to review the issue of media concentration after the
Premier League football deal with British Sky Broadcasting.
He told the British Society of Magazine Editors that a new investigation
would be in the interests of 'the poor viewer' whose sovereignty the 1990
Broadcasting Act was supposed to protect.
'On the evidence of the football deal and similar deals to come, Margaret
Thatcher's Broadcasting Act is short-changing the customers,' Mr Grade said.
He said News International told last year's Sadler inquiry into cross-media
promotion that it had not used the editorial contents of its newspapers
'unduly to promote Sky'. Mr Grade said the assurances given to the Sadler
committee were worthless.
News International is the biggest shareholder in BSkyB, in which Pearson,
owner of the Financial Times, has a stake.
