FT  30 MAY 92 / US growth revised up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US economy grew at an annual rate of 2.4 per cent in the first quarter,
rather than 2.0 per cent as initially reported, revised figures from the
Commerce Department indicated yesterday, writes Michael Prowse in
Washington.
This was the fourth consecutive quarter of growth and the best performance
for the US economy since the beginning of 1989. Many analysts, however, had
expected a bigger upward revision. The faster growth mainly reflected upward
revisions to corporate inventories and fixed investment, partially offset by
weaker net exports. The figures showed a sharp improvement in corporate
profitability in the first quarter.
