<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAY 92 / Hawks &amp; Handsaws: Not a bad day, quite the reverse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL THOMPSON-NOEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
I HAD a dream this week in which the outcome of next Wednesday's Epsom Derby
was revealed to me backwards. Time ran backwards, which meant that
everything happened in reverse: the Derby, my conversations with the Queen,
my journey to the racetrack. What prompted the dream, I'm sure, was Time's
Arrow, the Martin Amis novel, which I read last weekend. It tells the story
of a man's life backwards. (The man is a Nazi doctor at Auschwitz; with time
running backwards, he grows younger by the day, until he arrives at
childhood's innocence. We were all innocent, once).
My Derby dream was vivid. It started at the moment that a horse named Alnasr
Alwasheek, travelling backwards, left the finishing line last, which meant
he was first - two lengths behind Dr Devious, the horse I had backed. (The
Lester Piggott-ridden favourite, Rodrigo De Triano, was closer to last than
first, having been one of the first to cross the line).
'Tip-top]' said the Queen. 'Let's have some strawberries, then we'll meet
the owner. I'll send someone to fetch him.'
'An excellent race,' I agreed.
'Astonishing]' cried the Queen, raising her binoculars. 'Just as you
predicted] Is there clairvoyancy in your family? What a super race]'
As I watched, the runners moved backwards to Tattenham Corner, where there
was a certain amount of scrimmaging, then on up the hill and into the
starting stalls.
'They're off]' cried the Queen excitedly, lowering her binoculars.
Just before the Off], I raced downstairs, past the security guards and
across to the bookmakers. I handed a bookie a betting stub and he gave me
Pounds 500.
'Thankyou, sir.'
'Thankyou.'
'Certainly, sir. Pounds 5,000 to Pounds 500, Dr Devious.'
'Pounds 500 on Dr Devious, please.'
The Queen said: 'You've got about four minutes.'
I explained that I had not yet placed my bet.
'You certainly don't lack confidence. What a glorious afternoon] Have you
met the Queen Mother?'
'Dr Devious,' I said, 'though I am worried by Alnasr Alwasheek. Whatever the
outcome, there will be two lengths between them.'
'Such a shame,' agreed the Queen, 'but we can't have everything we want, can
we? What is your tip?'
'The Derby is easily my favourite race,' I told her. 'It is a pity that the
royal studs are without a runner this year.'
As most people know, the Queen is an expert on racing and breeding. She owns
many racehorses, though some are very slow. Despite her fabulous wealth, she
has had only scant success since unwisely selling one of her best horses,
Height of Fashion, to the Maktoum family of Dubai for a sum reckoned to have
been about Pounds 1.6m.
Last year (or was it next?) the Queen finished 69th on the UK owners' list,
with prizemoney of Pounds 62,168, immediately below a company called
Skeltools, which won Pounds 62,423. Her winnings were a drab pittance when
set against those of the leading owner, Sheikh Mohammed al Maktoum, who won
Pounds 1.84m. According to her apologists, the Queen's bloodstock operation
has to be seen to be self-financing and is extremely tightly budgeted, to
ward off political criticism.
The Queen said: 'So glad you could make it. I know that you like
horse-racing. As I said to my racing manager, so few of my relatives are now
suitable to be seen in public with me that I want to meet new people at
Epsom on Derby day. Young people. Bright people. New people.'
'Good afternoon, Ma'am.'
'Good afternoon, Mr Thompson-Noel,' said the Queen, her blue eyes
glittering. She was wearing a yellow dress and a strand of ancestral pearls.
She is grey and small now, but still vivacious and droll.
After leaving the track, I headed for the rail station. At the end of my
journey I went to the ticket office; I handed in my ticket and received
Pounds 12. Then I hailed a taxi. I gave the driver some change and he gave
me Pounds 8.
My long day was ending. I read the newspapers and poached myself an egg. I
bathed and shaved and gargled. Then I rolled into bed. What a splendid day,
I thought. Because I had backed a loser, I was Pounds 500 ahead, plus Pounds
42.80 for expenses.
Once you start going backwards, you can't afford to stop.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
