<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAY 92 / Finance and the Family: NS strategies / A look at the new
fixed-rate products
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TAKING an income from fixed-rate National Savings products is a complicated
process. After I had, in a recent article, made all the calculations for the
36th issue of certificates, the department promptly cancelled it. So, I went
back to my calculator and worked out the figures for the latest issue, the
37th.
It should be emphasised that these certificates are not designed to offer
income; they offer the best returns to those who hold them for the full five
years. Nevertheless, many people are unable to wait that long.
It is possible to create an income stream by cashing the certificates in
successive years. The 37th issue pays 5.5 per cent on the first anniversary;
6.2 per cent in the following year; 8 per cent in year three; 9.4 per cent
in year four; and 11 per cent in the final year, for an overall return of 8
per cent per annum. (No income is paid on certificates cashed in before the
first anniversary.)
Unlike the 36th issue, the 37th allows for a maximum investment of Pounds
7,500 (Pounds 15,000 for couples), although you can re-invest old
certificates up to a further Pounds 10,000. But before attempting any of
these strategies, investors should check to see if they can get a better
return elsewhere.
According to Colin Jackson, of Baronworth Investment Services, a return of
8.46 per cent is available on a Pounds 7,500 guaranteed income bond. Since
basic-rate tax is deducted from GIBs, basic-rate taxpayers will be better
off buying them than using National Savings. The certificates are really
only suitable vehicles for higher-rate taxpayers who want income.
Strategy one is designed to produce a level income and leave the capital
intact. By cashing Pounds 550, Pounds 525, Pounds 475 and Pounds 450 of
certificates in successive years, the investor can get an income of between
Pounds 574 and Pounds 595 a year. In the fifth year, he or she is left with
Pounds 5,500 of certificates. These mature with a value of Pounds 8,081.72,
leaving the investor to take Pounds 581.72 of income and Pounds 7,500 for
re-investment.
The average tax-free income has been around 7.8 per cent a year, compared
with the 8 per cent compound total return which would have been received by
leaving the money in for the full five years. In essence, the investor has
given up Pounds 600 of return to get the income.
Strategy two is designed to produce a steadily-growing income by cashing
certificates worth Pounds 500, Pounds 500, Pounds 475 and Pounds 475 in
successive years. The income will grow from Pounds 527 after year one to
Pounds 655 after year five. Again, the full Pounds 7,500 is left for
re-investment.
What about non-taxpayers? They will be interested primarily in the new
series-D capital bonds which pay a gross 10.75 per cent if held for five
years. (Taxpayers should note that they are taxed each year on the assumed
income from these bonds, even if they do not cash the bonds until the end of
year five).
Strategy three is designed to generate a steady income by investing Pounds
10,000 in the capital bonds. By cashing Pounds 950, Pounds 875, Pounds 800
and Pounds 725 of bonds in successive years, the investor can receive an
income of between Pounds 1,014 and Pounds 1,034.
At the end of year five, he will be left with certificates with a face value
of Pounds 6,650, which will mature for Pounds 11,080. He can take the Pounds
1,080 as the final year's income, leaving Pounds 10,000 for re-investment.
But the investor would have received around Pounds 1,500 more if he had left
in the money for the full term.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                              STRATEGY ONE
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Year                 Capital              Units              Income
           retained (Pounds)   encashed (Pounds)   received (Pounds)
1993                   6,950               550               580.25
1994                   6,425               525               588.25
1995                   5,950               475               574.77
1996                   5,500               450               595.70
1997                     n/a             5,500               581.72
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
After taking income in 1997, Pounds 7,500 is left for reinvestment.
Total return Pounds 2,920.66; if initial investment had been retained,
then Pounds 3,520.52.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                              STRATEGY TWO
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Year                 Capital              Units              Income
           retained (Pounds)   encashed (Pounds)   received (Pounds)
1993                  7,000                 500              527.50
1994                  6,500                 500              560.21
1995                  6,025                 475              574.77
1996                  5,550                 475              628.80
1997                    n/a               5,550              655.19
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
After taking income in 1997, Pounds 7,500 is left for reinvestment.
Total return is Pounds 2,946.47. If full amount had been retained for
five years, return would have been Pounds 3,520.52.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                             STRATEGY THREE
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Year                 Capital              Units              Income
           retained (Pounds)   encashed (Pounds)   received (Pounds)
1993                   9,050                950            1,018.40
1994                   8,175                875            1,014.92
1995                   7,375                800            1,017.93
1996                   6,650                725            1,034.90
1997                     n/a              6,650            1,080.02
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
After taking income in 1997, Pounds 10,000 is left for reinvestment.
Total return Pounds 5,165.67. If initial capital had been invested for
the full term, total return would have been Pounds 6,661.68.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
