<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Survey of Foreign Exchange (9): Currency trading matures -
Forex rooms are far more complex than before
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE popular image of foreign exchange dealers as the most frenzied of market
players  - young men burning with rage in front of computer screens,
slamming telephones on to desks while exchange rates flicker before their
eyes  - must now give way to a calmer, if occasionally frenetic, reality.
Forex dealing rooms are more complex places than they were. They are now
carefully integrated into their respective banks' operations in bonds,
domestic money markets and other activities.
Currencies are now far less volatile and in most banks, dealers spend less
time guessing whether government authorities will intervene on behalf of one
currency or another, and more looking for customers whose currency
portfolios they can manage.
Currency dealing is no less profitable. Forex can be among the most
lucrative markets in which any bank or corporation can invest. It is a
growing market, with a staggering global turnover of around Dollars 800bn a
day. 'It is easily the most consistent area for trading profits,' says Jim
O'Neill, head of research at Swiss Bank Corporation in London. 'It is far
more difficult for a bank to have a stable basis in bonds and equities than
in forex these days.'
But forex is no longer the dynamic and speculative arena it was a decade
ago. Then, it was populated by dozens of medium-sized banks and
corporations, ready to make quick profits on gyrating exchange rates. Now,
the operators are fewer in number and bigger in size, dominated by names
such as Citibank, UBS, Bankers Trust and Barclays, all of whom are
increasing their market share while smaller operators gradually leave the
market.
Three factors have brought about the shift in the balance of power:
First, it is harder to make quick profits in currency dealing because
exchange rates are far less volatile than a decade ago. From the mid-1980s,
the Group of Seven leading industrial nations decided that they shared a
common interest in defeating inflation and intervened in the market to
manage their exchange rates.
G7 policy co-ordination is still strong, in spite of recent tensions over
the extent to which Germany and Japan are prepared to loosen their
respective fiscal policies and help improve the global economy  - G7 finance
ministers have managed to keep the Japanese yen strong against the US dollar
after stating last month that a strong yen was essential for world economic
adjustment. Central bank intervention has also become less dramatic. In the
1980s, market-makers could still gamble on how central banks might
intervene. Now the process has become more technical. 'Central Banks make
much more subtle changes,' says Mark Slater, managing director of forex at
Merrill Lynch in London, 'and intervention is more often a smoothing
process, not an attempt to turn the market. The market players, instead of
saying 'Let's take the central banks on' admit that the authorities will win
in the end.'
The second pressure is the spread of the so-called 'Basle mentality' in
international banking. Since July 1988, when the central bankers of the
world's leading countries agreed on minimum capital adequacy ratios for
international banks, awareness of credit and counterparty risk has grown.
Recession in the English-speaking world, with its trail of bad debts and the
downgrading of banks by rating agencies, has encouraged prudence in
international banking.
Third, the advent of global financial trading has meant exchange rate
movements are increasingly affected by huge financial flows rather than
trade. In the 1980s, market-makers in foreign exchange would be sufficiently
well-informed about currency flows by having a handful of large corporate
clients. Today, they need lines to fund managers all over the world if they
are to compete effectively in the market. Banks and corporations have
responded in several ways to these new pressures.
The big banks are increasingly concentrating on the development of a secure
customer base, a policy which underpins the risks they take in trading on
their own capital. Citibank, one of the biggest, with around 10 per cent of
the London market, is proud of its customer service. 'Around half our
traders are engaged in the market, and the other half are talking to
customers,' says Julian Simmonds, Citibank's managing director of forex.
'You have to get the balance right these days between customers and risk.'
Investment banks dealing in forex also believe that customers matter, if for
different reasons. Mr Slater of Merrill Lynch says that the growth in forex
trading at his investment house is due to the demands of fund managers for
'currency overlay'. This is especially necessary, given the six-point
differential between short-term interest rates in Germany and the Federal
Bank's funds rate in the US.
'More and more, we see pension funds farming out the currency side of their
portfolios,' he says. 'Eighty or 90 per cent of our revenue is now from
client-generated business. If we don't have a client base with massive
growth we will be left behind.'
In addition, foreign exchange dealers need to be constantly on the look-out
for new markets to counteract the fall in exchange rate volatility. Mr
Simmonds of Citibank believes that the market will contract further with
European Monetary Union. 'There will be less volatility as the currencies
converge,' he says, 'and we will have to look beyond the frontiers of Europe
for new currencies to trade.'
He has his sights set on two regions. First, the currencies of Latin
America, whose equity markets were among the best performers last year.
Second, the currencies of eastern Europe, above all the Russian rouble. 'As
Russia moves towards full convertibility, we need to be involved,' he says.
'If the options close in European currencies, other opportunities must open
up.'
