<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / London Stock Exchange: Canary Wharf move upsets equities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEWS that Canary Wharf, the docklands property development, is being put
into administration provided the trigger for another round of profit-taking
and general selling pressure in London.
Worries that the latest moves could lead to the big UK banks taking
substantial provisions against their loans to Olympia &amp; York, developers of
Canary Wharf, knocked share prices of the banks and caused tremors
throughout the rest of the market. The selling took its toll of a market
that has seemingly run out of steam as the end of the long three-week
trading account looms.
London was also subdued by the absence of any substantial interest from the
Continent, where a number of markets were closed for Ascension Day. The
FT-SE Index lost 4.4 at 2,694.2, extending the fall this week to almost 21
points.
The day began with the Footsie future leading the cash market sharply lower
on the Canary Wharf news, the June contract dropping again to a discount to
fair value. Both the futures and the cash market quickly rallied, however,
with the Footsie, down almost seven points early in the session, recovering
strongly to post a gain of more than eight points by mid-morning.
Over lunch, the markets began to wilt afresh, worried by the prospect of yet
more bad news from the property arena. The Footsie retreated to show a fall
of 9.2 before embarking on a modest late rally, helped by the relatively
good showing by Wall Street, which was up eight points as London closed.
There was more good news on turnover, with customer business on Wednesday,
admittedly boosted by a big programme trade, expanding to Pounds 1.315bn.
Turnover yesterday amounted to 520.7m shares.
Tesco, the supermarket group, produced the best performance among the
Footsie constituents, still responding to switching operations being carried
out by leading brokers, involving the sale of cyclical stocks and the
purchase of more defensive issues.
BAT Industries, the tobacco to insurance group, rose strongly after
encouraging remarks by the chairman at the annual meeting. Retailing group
Sears also made good progress. On the downside, Taylor Woodrow fell almost 8
per cent, with some large lines of stock said to have been on offer. British
Steel was weak after Smith New Court adopted a bearish stance on the shares.
Suggestions that next Wednesday's preliminary figures from Siebe may include
a rights issue were rejected by dealers, but not before the shares had
fallen sharply.
British Gas, one of the market's best performers over the past week amid
stories that a break-up of the company may be in the offing, turned easier
after Moody's Investors Service, the US rating agency, said it was
considering downgrading Gas's debt ratings.
Vodafone, the cellular radio group, was persistently sold after news that
the merger of US groups Sprint and Centel implied lower cellular valuations.
Cable and Wireless was hit by disappointing results from its near 60 per
cent owned associate Hong Kong Telecom, while oil shares ran out of steam.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 40
</PAGE>
