<DATE>920529
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Names at odds over the pace of protest: Action taken by
Lloyd's members
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THIS WEEK'S bitter attack by Mr Peter Nutting on other prominent figures
among Lloyd's Names highlights the difficulties of organising a group of
individuals unaccustomed to collective action and political manoeuvring. It
has also illustrated the depth of divisions among the loss-making Names at
the insurance market.
Attracted by the prospect of easy money and social cachet, Lloyd's Names -
the individuals whose assets back underwriting at the insurance market -
traditionally have had little interest in campaigning.
Over the past few years that attitude has changed. Just under half of
Lloyd's 22,400 Names have joined the Association of Lloyd's Members, which
since its formation in the early 1980s has become the broad representative
body for all Names.
The association's focus, however, is on the provision of information and
advice to its members - all of whom face unlimited liability for any
insurance losses - and it cannot hope to advance the interests of the
substantial minority of Names who have suffered severe losses.
As a result, Names on loss-making syndicates have begun to form their own
organisations. Several thousand Names are either taking or contemplating
legal proceedings against their agents, and in one case against Lloyd's
itself, on grounds of negligence or a failure of duty of care.
More than a dozen associations or action groups have been created, and
groups have also appointed public-relations advisers to lead press and media
campaigns on their behalf.
Mr Nutting is himself a prominent figure in this growing movement, having
led a successful legal campaign for 1,000 Outhwaite Names which resulted in
a Pounds 116m out-of-court settlement in February. In April Mr Nutting
agreed to chair a new umbrella group of loss-making Names - the Lloyd's
Names Associations Working Party. With the Lloyd's Council indicating that
it was prepared to help badly affected Names, the working-party group might
have provided the Names with a way to negotiate a settlement outside the
courts.
However, Mr Nutting resigned last week, saying that he could not work with
Names' leaders who were opposed to this more moderate approach. 'Some
leaders and members of the committees of some action groups are involved in
a highly organised campaign of vilification against Lloyd's, its council and
most of those who earn their living on the market,' Mr Nutting said.
He urged other Names to reject the leadership of what he called
'extremists', and attacked efforts to obtain injunctions to prevent Lloyd's
drawing down on the deposits which all Names must lodge with their agents
when they join the market.
Mr Nutting suggested also that Names' groups should be more patient about
the pace of their legal campaigns.
However, many Names on another group of loss-making Lloyd's syndicates have
supported more radical action and reject Mr Nutting's advice as representing
the interests of the Lloyd's establishment. Those radicals are in no mood
for compromise. They are among 6,000 or so Names who are members of
syndicates - such as those managed by the Gooda Walker and Feltrim agencies
 -which specialised in catastrophe or spiral reinsurance, in which Lloyd's
syndicates and London market companies reinsure each others' exposure to
catastrophe loss, and which have borne a large share of Lloyd's losses. Many
joined the market recently and with relatively few assets are ill placed to
meet the losses that have emerged after the series of catastrophes that
shook world insurance markets between 1988 and 1990.
Their anger of Names at the scale of their losses has been fuelled by
evidence that members' agents may have mis-represented the character of the
risks to which Names were exposed, and by the degree to which the market's
overall losses have been concentrated in relatively few syndicates.
Mr Alfred Doll-Steinberg, chairman of the Gooda Walker Action Group, the
biggest single action group, which represents 2,100 Names, has been the most
publicly visible radical. He rejects the 'pay now, sue later' advice
proffered by moderates such as Mr Nutting.
Mr Doll-Steinberg's group's has launched an attempt to seek a judicial
review of Lloyd's. Mr Doll-Steinberg's legal adviser, Mr Richard Astor, has
also started a separate lobbying group, the Names Fraud Action Group.
The Distressed Names LMX Spiral Action Group, led by Mr Andrew Grossman, a
US lawyer and Name, has attempted to unite Names on other spiral syndicates
behind the more radical approach. His group is planning its own effort to
seek injunctions as well as launching a legal action alleging negligence.
Mr Grossman has been connected with litigation in the United States, where
about 100 Names are alleging breaches by Lloyd's of US securities laws when
it recruited them.
Both Mr Doll-Steinberg and Mr Grossman have been vigorous lobbyists. As well
as winning support in the press, Names have fought a highly effective
campaign in parliament, making common cause with a group of Conservative
MPs, many of whom are themselves Names. Extensive use of parliamentary
privilege has been made to promote allegations by MPs from both main parties
of insider trading - which say outsiders were stuffed on to the LMX or
'dustbin' syndicates while insider working Names creamed off the safest and
most profitable business for themselves.
Tensions between the more moderate and radical approaches have come to the
surface recently as leading executives at the Corporation of Lloyd's
examines the mechanics of its bail-out plan.
Mr Nutting's resignation may well set back these efforts. It indicates that
it may be difficult to reconcile the instincts of more moderate Names with
those of the more militant. That might make a compromised deal for Names
harder to achieve and must make it all the more likely that the legal action
dogging the market will continue.
</TEXT>
