<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Old spectres haunt the party:  Labour's past still threatens
its future
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS Labour's leadership election grinds on into its second month, the party
appears ever more unable to avoid reminding the electorate just how fiercely
conservative and anachronistic its basic instincts remain.
A process that started with pledges that no stone would be unturned in the
pursuit of modernisation and renewal this week saw the national executive,
Mr Neil Kinnock, the outgoing leader, and all three candidates for the
deputy leadership swear undying fealty to maintaining the party's historic
union links.
Meanwhile, newspaper readers have become reacquainted with the world of
block votes and union-executive recommendations.
Rather than spark debate, the leadership race has reinforced traditional
positions as candidates have vied for the votes of the party faithful. On
Wednesday the Fabian Society met in Westminster Central Hall - two
appositely early-20th-century institutions - to hear the deputy leadership
contenders stolidly oppose any tampering with Clause Four, the party's
controversial commitment to public ownership.
In consequence, Labour more and more resembles the political equivalent of
the Church of England - an introverted minority cult whose ageing followers
draw strength from an ancient litany of values, all but forgotten by the
fast-moving world outside.
Yet in spite of that, the internal power struggle might have a crucial
bearing on the party's hopes of power.
No one seriously doubts that Mr John Smith, the shadow chancellor, will win
the leadership at a trot. The real struggle is for the deputy leadership - a
largely symbolic post that, precisely for symbolic reasons, will carry
important messages to the electorate as to what Labour represents.
The choice before Labour's electoral college is between an establishment
candidate, a self-styled radical reformer and a party traditionalist.
Mr Margaret Beckett is known to be Mr Smith's preferred choice. A one-time
leftwinger, a woman and English, her curriculum vitae meshes well with his -
as does her proven ability as shadow chief secretary to grapple with the
awkward political decisions involved in constructing a formula for
democratic socialism on a limited budget.
Many, though, find Mrs Beckett's candidature lacklustre, based above all on
her gender and her promise not to rock Mr Smith's boat.
Yesterday she tried to meet those criticisms by tabling a manifesto. It
promised such items as a 'poverty census', a charter offering lifelong
access to education and a Citizenship Commission to press for public funding
for political parties. But the package smacked more of marketing strategies
than of conviction.
Such a charge could also be levelled at Mr Bryan Gould's headily ambitious
offerings, such as Europe-wide initiatives for full employment.
In reality, the environment spokesman's case rests not on his - widely
disputed - credentials as a radical reformer but on his subtle combination
of political guile and voter appeal that carries undoubted credibility in
middle-class southern England.
By contrast, Mr John Prescott's candidature has been described by one of his
rivals as 'a cry of pain' from the increasingly marginalised traditional
blue-collar Labour vote.
Disarmingly aware of his public-relations limitations, the bluntly spoken
transport spokesman has pitched for the deputy's job as an opportunity to
shake up the party organisation.
About 10 days ago, Westminster rumours suggested that the Smith camp was
'talking up' Mr Prescott's candidature to undermine Mr Gould and bolster a
perceived flagging in the Beckett campaign. Now it appears that growing
momentum behind Mr Prescott, particularly among some blue-collar unions, has
thrown that strategy into reverse.
Several 'modernisers' supporting the shadow chancellor are coming to the
view that it would be far better to live with the creative tensions
inevitable in a Smith-Gould leadership than to end up having to offer the
voters Mr Smith and Mr Prescott - two essentially old-fashioned and possibly
electorally catastrophic versions of Labour's image.
Mr Gould's supporters believe that if he can get through to the second round
of the ballot he can win a straight run-off against either of his rivals.
Like Mr Prescott's team, they think there is strong union and constituency
party resistance to the 'dream ticket' of Smith-Beckett.
Mr Gould himself concedes that there is a real difficulty in persuading the
electoral college - in which the unions have 40 per cent, MPs and MEPs 30
per cent and constituencies 30 per cent - to vote for him both for the
leadership and the deputy posts.
Ironically, if leftwing opponents of the party establishment opt for a
Gould-Prescott protest vote, it may result in the shadow environment
secretary losing out on both jobs and letting Mr Prescott through. One Gould
campaigner said: 'Our problem is all in the first round.'
As the Tories lick their lips at the prospect of a Smith-Prescott
leadership, many neutral observers believe that only Mr Gould has the
southern appeal and potential for imaginative leaps that the pragmatic,
Scottish Mr Smith will need to broaden his appeal.
With just over six weeks to go before balloting - and in spite of the
crucial importance of the result - it looks equally clear that no one has
the vaguest notion of what that outcome will be.
</TEXT>
