<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Fimbra entrants will face exam
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FINANCIAL advisers seeking to become members of Fimbra, the regulatory body
for independent advisers, will face a compulsory examination from September.
The move comes after criticism that some Fimbra members have provided
below-standard service to investors.
Last year some payouts to investors in collapsed companies were delayed
after the investors' compensation scheme, which was set up to protect
investors against bad advice, ran into funding difficulties because of the
number of claims against Fimbra members.
The examination announcement yesterday is part of a scheme designed to raise
the standards of both new and existing members of the watchdog organisation.
At present, financial advisers hoping to become members of Fimbra must have
had two years' relevant experience before they join, and do not have to take
an examination.
Last year the organisation introduced a voluntary entrance examination,
which will become compulsory in September for new entrants.
Mr Godfrey Jillings, chief executive of Fimbra, acknowledged yesterday that
'the standard (of the examination) is below the minimum standard we believe
necessary'. He said that efforts were being made to upgrade it 'in due
course'.
Under the new scheme, members will draw up a personal programme to include a
mixture of training, updating of knowledge, and study for qualifications in
different areas of financial advice.
The scheme is due to come into effect next year, and a pilot study is being
launched between July and December this year into its feasibility.
Mr Brian Cochrane, a Fimbra council member, said the aim was to educate
Fimbra members in order to benefit the consumer. Fimbra has been criticised
for laxity in regulating its members, but Mr Jillings said that it was
unrealistic to expect high standards overnight.
In a related move, the Securities and Investments Board the City's chief
investment watchdog, said yesterday that it had set up a panel to advise the
board on the training and competence plans for self-regulatory organisations
such as Fimbra and recognised professional bodies.
The panel will be chaired by Mr Leonard Warwick, a member of SIB's board and
a former president of the Life Insurance Association.
The new training and competence procedures are a result of proposals made
nearly two years ago by Ms Oonagh McDonald, former Labour MP, in a report
for SIB.
</TEXT>
