   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HUNGARY yesterday won backing from Mr John Major, the UK prime minister, for
its claim to be the first in the queue of former communist states waiting to
join the European Community, writes Philip Stephens in Budapest. A joint
declaration signed by Mr Major and Mr Jozsef Antall, his Hungarian
counterpart, included an explicit recognition of Budapest's ambition to be
part of the EC before the end of the century.
Mr Major, who arrived in Hungary after a visit to Prague, was accused
yesterday by Slovak nationalists of intervening in Czechoslovakia's general
election. He had said in the Slovak capital, Bratislava, that Britain
favoured maintaining the federation of the Czech lands and Slovakia. Mr
Jozef Prokes, leader of the secessionist Slovak National Party, was quoted
as saying: 'The visit's taking place before the election was no accident.'
