<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / US presses for Serbian oil embargo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, PHILIP STEPHENS and LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US last night pressed for an immediate oil embargo against Serbia as
part of a tough package of United Nations sanctions aimed at stopping the
ethnic conflict in the breakaway Yugoslav republics.
A State Department official said Britain, France and Belgium had agreed to
go along with the harder line against Serbia, dropping their proposals to
put off an oil embargo to the second stage of a sanctions programme.
But the US now had to win over other members of the 15-nation UN Security
Council, notably China and Russia. China has already made plain it objects
to sanctions and Russia opposes an oil embargo, but neither is expected to
block action by using its veto - an extreme step now out of favour at the
UN.
Western nations were hoping the Security Council would pass a sanctions
resolution today. But the tougher US intervention could delay agreement
because of more difficult negotiations.
The US bid to sharpen international action against Serbia came as Serb
irregular forces last night fired further barrages of rockets and artillery
shells on Sarajevo, the besieged capital of the breakaway republic of
Bosnia-Hercegovina. The missiles came from Serb positions in the wooded
hills ringing the city.
Earlier, there was a lull in the fighting around Sarajevo after heavy
overnight clashes. In a bid to distance itself from Wednesday's mortar
attack on Sarajevo which left 17 dead and 80 wounded, the rump Yugoslav
presidency called on the UN to investigate the 'massacre'.
A European Community suggestion that UN troops should provide protection for
humanitarian aid efforts in Bosnia-Hercegovina was rejected by Mr Boutros
Boutros Ghali, the UN secretary-general. While acknowledging it was for the
Security Council to make a final decision, Mr Boutros Ghali warned that it
would require large numbers of UN troops to secure several hundred miles of
roads and to establish a defensive perimeter around Sarajevo.
The city has been cut off by Serb militia and Yugoslav federal army troops
in a bid to starve it into submission.
Mr John Major, on his visit to Budapest, said UN sanctions were likely to
include a trade embargo, a freeze on Serbia's overseas assets, severe
restrictions on commercial flights, the suspension of all official sporting
contacts and the break-off of scientific, technical and cultural
co-operation.
Under EC proposals, there was to be provision for an oil embargo from the
middle of next month if Serbia did not act to halt the fighting.
The prime minister said the precise terms of the resolution were still under
discussion. 'But I hope it will be agreed by the United Nations by the end
of this week . . . that it will be a binding and mandatory series of
sanctions.'
In Belgrade the Serbian Orthodox Church attacked the policies of President
Slobodan Milosevic in an unprecedented open letter.
The church, which had supported the nationalist politics of Mr Milosevic,
yesterday appealed for his resignation and the formation of a government of
national salvation. Serbia's state-controlled media censored the memorandum.
