<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / PM rules out rescue but Tube line talks possible
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday ruled out a government rescue of Canary Wharf and
reaffirmed that the proposed extension of the Jubilee line depended on a
substantial contribution from the owners of the docklands development.
But, in what appeared to be a hint of flexibility over the details of the
rail financing package, the prime minister added that the government was
ready to listen to any new proposals made by the administrators.
He also emphasised that Whitehall departments would continue negotiations to
relocate upwards of 2,000 civil servants to the development as long as any
such move was 'on commercial terms'.
Speaking in Hungary at the end of a four-day visit to central Europe, Mr
Major said repeatedly that the enforced move into administration of Canary
Wharf had not changed his policy towards the project.
Under an agreement negotiated with Olympia &amp; York, the developer of Canary
Wharf, the government agreed to invest about Pounds 1.5bn to extend the
Jubilee line to docklands as long as the developers provided a total of
Pounds 400m towards the project. About Pounds 40m of that was due to be paid
by O&amp;Y in March with a further Pounds 60m next year and the remainder in
small instalments until well into the next century.
Last night, Mr Major said the agreement would stand with the creditors of
the development: 'We have agreed to spend around Pounds 1.5bn on the Jubilee
line but that is subject to the owners of Canary Wharf, whoever they are,
making a substantial contribution to the cost of the project and a further
contribution once the project is built'.
He added that 'nothing you should take from me suggests our position is
going to change'.
The hint of flexibility on the details came when Mr Major was pressed
repeatedly as to whether the administrators would have to agree precisely
the same conditions as those agreed with O&amp;Y. He responded: 'I think we
should wait and see what the administrators have to say. I'm not going to
prejudge that.'
Senior officials travelling with the prime minister stressed that the
comment did not imply he was ready to increase the government's financial
contribution.
The remarks, however, did suggest that Mr Major does not want to close the
door on the possibility of rescheduling the private sector contribution or
agreeing to a delay in the line's construction timetable. Mr Michael
Heseltine, president of the board of trade, is expected to be among
ministers arguing over the next few days that the government should try to
help the project.
</TEXT>
